Interesting clock sculpture located outside the Gare Saint-Lazare Station.  "A man with a watch always knows what time it is, a man with two watches is never quite sure".

This is a cool sculpture made up of a tower of many clocks. It reflects the importance of time to every traveler. You can find it right outside of Gare Saint Lazare, and it is worth a look or a photo if you happen to pass by here.

The original monument. And the place on the square in front of the Saint-Lazare station is symbolic, because the station is a place of people always in a hurry.  You can no longer ask the sculptor what idea he wanted to convey to us. About the inexorable transience of time or its value. But in any case, this work makes you think about how we manage our time. Have a nice day and good trip.

A beautiful station with an original work in place in the courtyard of Le Havre: "L'heure de tous" by the artist Arman (1923-2005)...known for his accumulations of objects...and in the courtyard of Rome another of his works: "Lifetime lock-up"... Ideal for a station! To have !
I thought it was cool

That at the doors of a train station with such a large volume of passengers, there is a sculpture consisting of a gigantic stack of clocks, is truly suggestive. If there is something that travelers value, it is time. This sculpture, the work of the artist Arman, is framed within what is called "Nouveau Realisme" and consists of using elements from everyday life to provoke reactions in the viewer.
Although it is a single place with this monument, it has always seemed like a nice place to us. We recommend it as a place to stop by and take a photo.

L'heure de tous, is a work by the French artist Arman created in 1985.  It is located in Cour du Havre just in front of Saint Lazare station.  This work is composed of an accumulation of bronze clocks, it is part of the artist's approach to accumulate everyday objects that bear witness to the human cycle of mass manufacturing, consumption and then destruction.
Statue placed in front of the station, truly particular

Bronze sculpture with dimensions 460x125x182 cm. made in 1985, by the French sculptor (artist, painter) Arman who lived between 1928-2005 (also in the same year he made "Consigne a vie" exhibited in the Court of Rome in Saint-Lazare station).
